The '''Movement for a Europe of Nations and Freedom''' ({{lang-fr|Mouvement pour l’Europe des nations et des libertés}}), abbreviated to '''MENL''' or '''MENF''', is an alliance of European political parties founded in 2014. Its political group in the European Parliament is [[Europe of Nations and Freedom]].

==History==
In  the aftermath of the [[European Parliament election, 2014]], parties affiliated with the [[European Alliance for Freedom]] unsuccessfully attempted to form a [[Political groups of the European Parliament|political group]] in the [[European Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/europe/article4102623.ece |title=Le Pen party steals Farage’s Italian allies |publisher=The Times |date=2014-05-29 |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/24/marine-le-pen-fails-form-far-right-bloc-european-parliament |title=Marine Le Pen fails to form far-right bloc in European parliament &#124; World news |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/le-pens-far-right-eu-parliament-alliance-fails-start-1453971 |title=Le Pen's Far-Right EU Parliament Alliance Fails at Start |publisher=Ibtimes.co.uk |date=2014-06-24 |accessdate=2015-11-04}}</ref>

Later in 2014, they decided to create a new European-level structure, which became the Movement for a Europe of Nations and Freedom. The Dutch [[Party for Freedom]] (PVV) chose not to participate in this pan-European party, as it declined to be funded by the European Union.<ref name=mudde>{{cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/can-europe-make-it/cas-mudde/eaf-is-dead-long-live-menl|title=The EAF is dead! Long live the MENL!|author=[[Cas Mudde]]|work=[[openDemocracy]]|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> The Polish [[Congress of the New Right]] (KNP), initially claimed that it would be part of the new alliance, but was accused in a press release by the French [[National Rally (France)|National Rally]] of spreading false claims in the Polish and Austrian media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontnational.com/2014/10/communique-daymeric-chauprade-chef-de-delegation-du-front-national-au-parlement-europeen/|title=Communiqué d’Aymeric Chauprade, chef de Délégation du Front National au Parlement européen|work=Front National|accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> Ultimately the KNP took part in the creation of the party's new parliamentary group as its former controversial leader [[Janusz Korwin-Mikke]] was evicted from the party to be replaced by Michal Marusik.

It was recognised by the European Parliament (EP) in 2015. Its maximum grant by the EP for this year is €1,170,746<ref name="EPgrantamounts_2015">[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/pdf/grants/Grant_amounts_parties%2003-2015_new%20logo.pdf "Grants from the European Parliament to political parties at European level 2004-2015"], March 2015, Europarl.europa.eu, retrieved 27 April 2015</ref> plus €621,677 for its affiliated [[Political foundation at European level|political foundation]], the ''Fondation pour une Europe des Nations et des Libertés''.<ref>[http://www.europarl.europa.eu/pdf/grants/Grant_amounts_foundations%2003-2015_new%20logo.pdf "Grants from the European Parliament to political foundations at European level 2008-2015"], March 2015, Europarl.europa.eu/, retrieved 27 April 2015</ref>

On 16 June 2015, the [[Europe of Nations and Freedom]] parliamentary group was created in the [[European Parliament]] with members of the MENL (RN, FPÖ, LN, VB) as well as the PVV, Poland's [[Congress of the New Right|KNP]] and a former member of [[UKIP]], [[Janice Atkinson]].

The 1st congress of the movement was held on 28 June 2015 in [[Perpignan]], [[France]] gathering some [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]] from the [[National Rally (France)|National Rally]] as well as a few of its local & national representatives members; the objective of this meeting was mainly about making the 1st year of action of the National Rally's MEPs in review.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lindependant.fr/2015/06/27/a-perpignan-le-front-national-accuse-l-europe-et-le-pouvoir,2050944.php|title=À Perpignan, le Front national accuse l’Europe et le pouvoir (notre interview video de Marine Le Pen)|date=27 June 2015}}</ref>

On 15 September 2015, the Flemish [[Vlaams Belang]] (VB) and the movement organised a colloquium dealing with sovereignty which took place in the [[Flemish Parliament]] with VB's leader [[Tom Van Grieken]], MEP [[Gerolf Annemans]], VB's member Barbara Pas and [[National Rally (France)|National Rally]]'s leader [[Marine Le Pen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grenzenstellen.eu/ |title=Colloquium Soevereiniteit: Grenzen Stellen |website=Grenzenstellen.eu |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref> All of the Flemish parties approved [[Marine Le Pen]]'s visit at the Flemish Parliament although the speaker of the Flemish Parliament [[Jan Peumans]] ([[New Flemish Alliance|N-VA]]) decided not to be part of this colloquium.<ref>{{cite web|author=Frédéric Chardon |url=http://www.lalibre.be/actu/politique-belge/tous-les-partis-flamands-ont-approuve-la-venue-de-marine-le-pen-55f832ff3570b0f19ea60dbd#.VfhVlpB_xFZ.twitter |title=Tous les partis flamands ont approuvé la venue de Marine Le Pen |website=La Libre.be |date=2015-09-15 |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>

On 24 October 2015, MENL's leader and vice-president of the National Rally [[Louis Aliot]] met the current president of [[Brothers of Italy]], [[Giorgia Meloni]] in [[Trieste]] for a conference on immigration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fratelli-italia.it/2015/10/20/immigrazione-sabato-24-ottobre-confronto-a-trieste-tra-giorgia-meloni-e-il-vicepresidente-del-front-national-louis-aliot/ |title=Fratelli d'Italia – Alleanza Nazionale &#124; Immigrazione, sabato 24 ottobre confronto a Trieste tra Giorgia Meloni e il vicepresidente del Front National, Louis Aliot |website=Fratelli-italia.it |date=2015-10-20 |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>

[[Marine Le Pen]] praised [[Swiss People's Party|SVP]]'s victory during the [[Swiss federal election, 2015|2015 Swiss election]] although the Swiss party does not have official links with the movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letemps.ch/suisse/2015/10/19/victoire-udc-beaucoup-francais-enthousiastes |title=Victoire de l'UDC: beaucoup de Français enthousiastes - Le Temps |language=fr|website=Letemps.ch |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref> The movement also launched an anti-immigration campaign in 2015 just like the [[Swiss People's Party|SVP]]'s campaign during [[Swiss immigration referendum, February 2014|Swiss referendum on immigration]] in 2014.

On 21 November 2015, MENL's think thank "Foundation for a Europe of Nations and Freedom" organised a colloquium ("L'euro, un échec inéluctable?") dealing with [[Euro]] and how it might be an inescapable failure. [[Jacques Sapir]] took part in this colloqium among others. The FENF, chaired by [[Gerolf Annemans]], organised another colloquim on 2 April 2016 in [[Paris]] dealing with union representation and the development of professional organisations in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fenl.eu/contact/ |title=Foundation for a Europe of Nations and Freedom - Contact |website=Fenl.eu |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>

The third colloquium of the movement took place on 4 March 2016 in the [[Flemish Parliament]]  with VB's leader [[Tom Van Grieken]] and [[Party for Freedom|PVV]]'s leader [[Geert Wilders]]. This colloquim entitled "Freedom" ("Vrijheid") dealt with liberties in Europe and how they would be threatened by immigration from "countries with cultures which are fundamentally different [from the European one]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colloquiumvrijheid.eu/ |title=Colloquium Vrijheid |website=Colloquiumvrijheid.eu |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>

The movement's member parties and allies met in July 2016 in Vienna, an event hosted by Austria's FPÖ. The French National Rally, [[Matteo Salvini]]'s Northern League, the AfD, Belgium's [[Vlaams Belang]], the Dutch Party for Freedom were present among other independent politicians and smaller European parties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/europes-right-wing-parties-meet-near-vienna-urge-brexit/a-19339474 |title=Europe's right-wing parties meet near Vienna, urge Brexit |publisher=DW.COM |date=2016-06-17 |accessdate=2017-03-17}}</ref>

According to [[Politico]], the movement owed in 2016 the [[European Parliament]] €535,818. The reasons given by Politico were the forbidden use of European grants by the MENL party to finance national political parties and referendum campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|last=Posaner |first=Joshua |url=http://www.politico.eu/article/national-front-marine-le-pen-far-right-groups-ordered-to-pay-european-parliament-e800000/ |title=Far-right groups ordered to pay European Parliament €800,000 |publisher=Politico.eu |date=2016-09-03 |accessdate=2017-03-17}}</ref> The party strongly denied these allegations by saying that they just had to give the unused EU funds back to the European Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.menleuropa.eu/2016/09/15/response-to-the-shameless-lies-of-the-website-politico/ |title=Response to the shameless lies of the website Politico |publisher=Movement for a Europe of Nations and Freedom |date=2016-09-15 |accessdate=2017-03-17}}</ref>

