'''Project Clear Vision''' was a covert examination of [[Soviet Armed Forces|Soviet]]-made biological [[bomblet]]s conducted by the [[Battelle Memorial Institute]] under contract with the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]]. The legality of this project under the [[Biological Weapons Convention]] (BWC) of 1972 is disputed.{{where?|date=February 2013}}
==History== ===The operation=== Project Clear Vision was conducted between 1997 and 2000,<ref name=enemark/> during the [[Clinton Administration]].<ref name=miller>[[Judith Miller (journalist)|Miller, Judith]], Engelberg, Stephen and [[William J. Broad|Broad, William J.]] "[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?sec=health&res=9E02E1D71639F937A3575AC0A9679C8B63 U.S. Germ Warfare Research Pushes Treaty Limits]", ''[[The New York Times]]'', September 4, 2001. Retrieved January 6, 2009.</ref> The project's stated goal was to assess the efficacy of [[bio-agent]] dissemination from bomblets.<ref name=tucker/> The program received criticism due to suspicions that its findings could possibly be used in a covert US [[bioweapons]] program.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}
===Reportage=== The secret project was disclosed in a September 2001 article in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=enemark/> Reporters [[Judith Miller (journalist)|Judith Miller]], Stephen Engelberg and [[William J. Broad]] collaborated to write the article.<ref name=enemark/> Shortly after the article appeared, the authors published a book that further elaborated the story.<ref name=enemark/> The 2001 book, ''[[Germs: Biological Weapons and America's Secret War]]'', and the article are the only publicly available sources{{citation needed|date=February 2013}} concerning Project Clear Vision and its sister projects, [[Project Bacchus|Bacchus]] and [[Project Jefferson|Jefferson]].<ref name=enemark>Enemark, Christian. ''Disease and Security: Natural Plagues and Biological Weapons in East Asia'', ([https://books.google.com/books?id=bT9j6lhPHHUC&pg=PA173&dq=%22Project+Clear+Vision%22&client=firefox-a#PPA174,M1 Google Books]), Routledge, 2007, pp. 173-75, ({{ISBN|0415422345}}).</ref>
==Legality== As signatory to the BWC, the United States is committed to refrain from development of [[bioweapons]]. Moreover, the US did not disclose the secret project in its annual confidence-building measure (CBM) declarations.<ref name=tucker>[[Tucker, Jonathan B]]. "[http://www.armscontrol.org/act/2004_10/Tucker.asp Biological Threat Assessment: Is the Cure Worse Than the Disease?]", ''Arms Control Today, October 2004. Retrieved January 6, 2009.</ref> The US maintains that the program was fully consistent with the BWC because the project was defensive in nature.<ref name=miller/>
